I found that Strands graph does not have the same level of AgentCore Memory support that Strands react does. 

Naturally I tried using the AgentCoreMemorySessionManager here, but it gave me errors. 

So I ended up having to use the AgentCore API via boto3 SDK. If you look at the invoke() function in src/research_agent.py, you'll notice 

```
    response = _ac_memory.list_events(
        memoryId=MEMORY_ID,
        sessionId=session_id,
        actorId=user_id,
        includePayloads=True, # Note: plural in raw Boto3
        maxResults=10 # Only get the last 5 turns (5 user + 5 assistant)
    )
```

and
```
_ac_memory.create_event(
        memoryId=MEMORY_ID,
        sessionId=session_id,
        actorId=user_id,
        eventTimestamp=datetime.now(timezone.utc),
        payload=[...
```

Whereas in ../research_agent.py/src/research_agent.py, we have

```
    memory_config = AgentCoreMemoryConfig(
        memory_id=MEMORY_ID,
        session_id=session_id,
        actor_id=user_id,
        retrieval_config={
            "/strategies/{actorId}/semantic": RetrievalConfig(
                top_k=3, relevance_score=0.2,
            ),
            "/strategies/{actorId}/preferences": RetrievalConfig(
                top_k=3, relevance_score=0.2,
            ),
        },
    )
    return AgentCoreMemorySessionManager(memory_config, REGION)
